{{multiple issues| {{coi|date=March 2018}} {{refimprove|date=March 2018}} }} {{infobox Museum |name = Saint Louis Science Center |image = Saint Louis Science Center Entrance.jpg |caption = Saint Louis Science Center Entrance |pushpin_map = Forest Park (St. Louis) |map_size = 220 |map_caption = |coordinates = {{coord|38.6289|-90.2708|type:landmark_region:US-MO_dim:3500|format=dms|display=inline,title}} |established = 1963 |location = 5050 Oakland Ave, [[St. Louis, Missouri]], United States |visitors = |director = |website = {{url|www.slsc.org}} }} The '''Saint Louis Science Center''', founded as a planetarium in 1963, is a collection of buildings including a [[science museum]] and [[planetarium]] in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], on the southeastern corner of [[Forest Park (St. Louis, Missouri)|Forest Park]]. With over 750 exhibits in a complex of over {{convert|300000|sqft|sqm}}, it is among the largest of its type in the United States.<ref name=scala>{{cite book|title=Forest Park, Saint Louis|author=Craske, Oliver|author2=Peacock, Sarah|author3=Shoolbred, Andrew|publisher=Scala Publishers|isbn=978-1-85759-340-2|date=2007}}</ref>{{page needed|date=March 2018}}
== James S. McDonnell planetarium ==<!-- This section is linked from [[St. Louis, Missouri]] --> [[File:McDonnellPlanetarium.jpg|thumb|320px|The James S. McDonnell Planetarium, built in 1963 and featuring a [[thin-shell structure|thin-shell]] and [[hyperboloid structure]] by [[Gyo Obata]]. This building is one of the most distinctive components of the Saint Louis Science Center campus]] Funding for the first structure of the current campus began in 1955, with $1 million of a $110 million city bond issue specified for the construction of a planetarium. Two years were spent surveying locations. The first proposed site, on the northern side of Forest Park near the [[Missouri History Museum|Jefferson Memorial Building]] at Lindell and DeBaliviere, was scrapped because of restrictions on subdivisions. The location was changed to the southern part of the park, on the site of the old [[mounted police]] station, which was demolished in 1960. The plan was to build a planetarium, science museum, and natural history museum.<ref name=fp/>
The Planetarium was designed by [[Gyo Obata]] of [[Hellmuth, Obata and Kassabaum]] with a unique shape (Obata was later tasked in the 1970s with designing the [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian]]'s [[National Air and Space Museum]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]). ''[[Architectural Forum]]'' magazine described it as, "Looking like some strange craft spun down to earth from outer space... St. Louis's new planetarium perches gracefully on a rise in ... Forest Park".<ref name=fp/> [[James Smith McDonnell]] (1899&ndash;1980), an aviation pioneer and co-founder of St. Louis-based [[McDonnell Douglas]], an [[aerospace manufacturer]], donated $200,000 for equipment such as the star projector. The facility was named after him in 1964.<ref name=fp>{{cite book|date=1986|isbn=0-9638298-0-7|author=Loughlin, Caroline|author2=Anderson, Catherine|title=Forest Park|publisher=[[University of Missouri Press]]|location=[[Columbia, Missouri]]|page=207&ndash;209}}</ref>
==Science center== [[File:Dinosaur Diorama at Saint Louis Science Center.jpg|thumb|Dinosaur diorama on the lower level]] In 1972, the Science Center in Clayton began to receive funds from sales tax through the [[Metropolitan Zoological Park and Museum District]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mzdstl.org/History.htm |title=History of the Metropolitan Zoological Park and Museum District |accessdate=2009-12-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100125165028/http://www.mzdstl.org/History.htm |archivedate=2010-01-25 |df= }}</ref> In 1983, the St. Louis [[Museum of Science and Natural History]] purchased the Planetarium from the city, and closed it for remodeling. On July 20, 1978, the Planetarium reopened as the Saint Louis Science Center.<ref name=jewel/>{{page needed|date=March 2018}} On November 2, 1991, as part of a $34 million expansion, a new building opened across from the Planetarium south of I-64, on Oakland Avenue, increasing the size of the Science Center by a factor of seven. The new building was constructed on land that had previously been the site of the [[Falstaff Brewing Corporation]] headquarters.<ref name=jewel/>{{page needed|date=March 2018}} New exhibits in the main building were devoted to [[Earth science]], [[emerging technology]], [[life sciences]], [[physical science]], and [[chemistry]].<ref name=jewel>{{cite book|title=The Jewel of St. Louis: Forest Park|last=Altman |first=Sally |author2=Weiss, Richard |date=2007|isbn=978-0-9796054-1-3|publisher=Walsworth Publishing Co.|location=[[Marceline, Missouri]]}}</ref><ref name=life>{{cite book|title=Bringing Science to Life: A Guide from the Saint Louis Science Center|date=2007|author=Corrigan, Patricia|isbn=978-1-933370-16-3|publisher=Virginia Publishing Co.}}</ref>{{page needed|date=March 2018}} Within two months, the newly remodeled Saint Louis Science Center became the most visited science center in the world.<ref name=jewel/>{{page needed|date=March 2018}}
[[File:Energizer Ball Machine.jpg|thumb|Energizer Ball Machine in lobby of main building]]
==Exhibitions== On February 8, 1997, an air-supported building was added to the main building, the Exploradome. With an additional {{convert|18000|sqft|sqm}}, it was intended as a temporary facility for traveling exhibitions, additional classrooms, and to host large group events. Notable exhibits have included shows on the ''[[RMS Titanic]]'' ocean liner, and [[Body Worlds]], a traveling exhibition of preserved human bodies.<ref name=life/><ref name=scala/>{{page needed|date=March 2018}} From October 2011 until May 2012, the main building hosted ''[[Star Trek: The Exhibition]]'', a major showcase of ''[[Star Trek]]'' props, costumes and artifacts, including a full-size bridge from the USS ''[[USS Enterprise (NCC-1701-D)|Enterprise]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slsc.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=zSJcZfHQYQo%3d&tabid=667|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404062839/http://www.slsc.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=zSJcZfHQYQo=&tabid=667|dead-url=yes|archive-date=April 4, 2012|title=Star Trek: The Exhibition opened at Saint Louis Science Center|date=September 22, 2011|accessdate=October 23, 2011|publisher=Saint Louis Science Center}}</ref>
=== WeatherReadyFest === The 2018 [[WeatherReadyFest]] event was held at the St. Louis Science Center featuring talks, demonstrations and displays from the [[National Weather Service]] and other government and private agencies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.stlamerican.com/news/local_news/free-weatherready-fest-at-science-center/article_932654b8-a0cc-11e8-8969-c74c880f1a49.html|title=Free WeatherReady Fest at Science Center|work=St. Louis American|access-date=2018-08-27|language=en}}</ref>
